%I A395250 #42 May 28 2026 18:51:54
%S A395250 1,1,4,74,8508,6460153
%N A395250 Number of metrizable convexities on a set of n elements.
%C A395250 A convexity C on a set X is a collection of subsets of X such that {} and X are in C, C is closed under arbitrary intersection, and C is closed under directed union.
%C A395250 A convexity C is said to be metrizable if there exists a metric d on X so that for all subsets A of X, we have that A is convex iff z in A for all x,y in A and z in X with d(x,z)+d(z,y)=d(x,y) (see van de Vel).
%C A395250 Note that every convexity C on X induced by a metric d comes from a betweenness relation B defined by B(x,z,y)<=>d(x,z)+d(z,y)=d(x,y) for all x,y,z in X. Specifically, A is in C iff z in A whenever x,y in A, z in X, and B(x,z,y).
%C A395250 The Python program in the Links enumerates a(n) by first computing metrizable betweenness relations on a set of n elements (see A395237). Interestingly, a(n)=A395237(n) for n<=4 (distinct betweenness relations induce distinct convexities), but a(n)<A395237(n) for n>4.
%C A395250 Every metrizable convexity on a set X is an interval convexity (see A364656), with intervals given by metric segments, so a(n)<=A364656(n).
%D A395250 M. L. J. van de Vel, Theory of Convex Structures, North-Holland Mathematical Library, vol. 50, North-Holland, Amsterdam, 1993.
%H A395250 Tian Vlasic, <a href="/A395250/a395250.py.txt">Python Program</a>
%e A395250 a(3)=4 as there are 4 metrizable convexities on X={a,b,c}:
%e A395250   {{},{a},{b},{c},{a,b},{a,c},{b,c},{a,b,c}},
%e A395250   {{},{a},{b},{c},{a,b},{a,c},{a,b,c}},
%e A395250   {{},{a},{b},{c},{a,b},{b,c},{a,b,c}}, and
%e A395250   {{},{a},{b},{c},{a,c},{b,c},{a,b,c}}.
%Y A395250 Cf. A395237, A364656, A102894.
%K A395250 nonn,more
%O A395250 1,3
%A A395250 _Tian Vlasic_, May 20 2026
%E A395250 a(6) from _Robert P. P. McKone_, May 24 2026
